data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","sequence_number":444,"item_id":"msg_0ba0ce59a2315fe400693b6747a5bc819386417c71619eaafe","output_index":3,"content_index":0,"text":"Do you mean \"secondary agent\" in a specific system (customer support, robotics, multi-agent AI, security, etc.)? If not, here are common roles a secondary agent can play and how they’re used:\n\nCommon roles\n- Backup/failover: take over when the primary fails or is overloaded.\n- Specialist/subsystem: handle a specific function (e.g., perception, validation, logging) while the primary handles strategy/coordination.\n- Monitor/auditor: observe actions, verify correctness, detect anomalies, and raise alerts.\n- Validator/verifier: independently check outputs from the primary to improve safety and correctness.\n- Coordinator/facilitator: manage message routing, synchronization, and conflict resolution among agents.\n- Data manager/preprocessor: collect, clean, filter, and annotate data for use by the primary.\n- Security/watchdog: enforce policies, detect intrusions, and quarantine risky activity.\n- Interface/translator: adapt protocols, formats, or languages between components.\n- Escalation/triage: handle common/simple cases and escalate complex cases to the primary or a human.\n- Experimenter/learner: run simulations, test hypotheses, and collect training data without risking the primary’s operation.\n\nExample mappings\n- Customer support: secondary drafts replies, tags intent, and suggests KB articles; primary (or human) approves final message.\n- Robotics: secondary handles localization and health checks; primary plans motion and mission goals.\n- Finance: secondary monitors transactions for fraud and flags suspicious ones to the primary analyst.\n- CI/CD: secondary runs tests and linters; primary makes release decisions based on results.\n\nDesign considerations / best practices\n- Clear separation of responsibilities and handoff procedures.\n- Well-defined communication protocols and shared state semantics.\n- Escalation rules and limits on autonomous actions for safety.\n- Robust logging, monitoring, and audit trails for accountability.\n- Timeouts, retries, and graceful degradation for reliability.\n- Performance and latency requirements for real-time systems.\n\nIf you tell me the domain or what the primary agent already does, I can suggest a concrete set of responsibilities, communication patterns, and safety rules for the secondary agent.","logprobs":[]}

